‘The Editor cannot dwell on anything later. Arthur accompanied him to Germany in the begin· ning of August. In returning to Vienna from Pesth, a wet day probably gave rise to an intermittent fever, with very slight symptoms, and apparently subsiding‚ when a sudden rush of blood to the head put an in· stantaneous end to his lile on the 15th os September 1833. The mysteriousness of such a dreadsul ter- mination toa disorder generally ol so little import- ance, and in this instance of the slightest kind, has been diminished by an examination which showed a weakness of the cerebral vessels, and a want of suffi- cient energy in the heart. Those whose eyes must long be dim with tears, and whose hopes on this side the tomb are broken down lor ever, may cling, as well as they can, to the poor consolation os be- lieving that a few more years would, in the usual chances of humanity, have severed the frail union of his grateful and manly form with the pure spirit that it enshrined.
